The paper deals with natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning techniques for handling large numbers of features, which are common topics in the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. The use of low-rank tensor approximations is a technique often used in machine learning and optimization, which suggests the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category as a likely fit. The paper also presents a new model for representing lexical features, which involves learning representations of words and contextual information, a topic that falls under the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The use of tensor representations and low-rank approximations is also relevant to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents results on tasks related to natural language understanding, which suggests the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category as a possible fit, given the overlap between NLP and computer vision in recent years.
